Data Wrangling

# making a copy (i.e. to not modify original data)
penguin_df <- penguins
  • Boolean variables take on the values either TRUE or FALSE
# boolean check to see if species is Gentoo
penguin_df <- penguin_df %>%
  mutate(Gentoo_bool = ifelse(species == "Gentoo", "is Gentoo", "not Gentoo"))
# boolean check to see if body mass in grams is over 4050
penguin_df <- penguin_df %>%
  mutate(size_bool = ifelse(body_mass_g > 4050, "large", "small"))
# generate 3 differen dataframes each with different species
Adelie_df <- penguins %>%
  filter(species == "Adelie")

Chinstrap_df <- penguins %>%
  filter(species == "Chinstrap")

Gentoo_df <- penguins %>%
  filter(species == "Gentoo")

Correlation

# graph the body mass of Gentoo panguins to their flipper length
penguins %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = body_mass_g, y = flipper_length_mm)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Palmer Penguins",
       subtitle = "scatterplot",
       caption = "Source: Palmer Penguins",
       x = "body mass (in grams)",
       y = "flipper length (in mm)")
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# calculate the Gentoo penguins Correlation value
penguins %>% 
  get_correlation(formula = flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g,
                  na.rm = TRUE)
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##     cor
##   <dbl>
## 1 0.871

Best-Fit Line

# generate a graph of the Chinstrap Penguins and add a line of best fit
Chinstrap_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = body_mass_g, y = flipper_length_mm)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + #"lm" for linear model
  labs(title = "Chinstrap Penguins",
       subtitle = "linear regression",
       caption = "Source: Palmer Penguins",
       x = "body mass (in grams)",
       y = "flipper length (in mm)") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

# calculate the y-intercept and the x-intercept
lin_fit <- lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = Chinstrap_df)
lin_fit
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = Chinstrap_df)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)  body_mass_g  
##   151.38087      0.01191
  • \(y\): true outcomes (outputs from the data itself)
  • \(\hat{y}\): estimates (outputs from regression model)
  • \(y - \hat{y}\): residuals
# generate a table of all the Regression variables for both the y and x axis
get_regression_table(lin_fit)
## # A tibble: 2 x 7
##   term        estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 intercept    151.        6.58      23.0        0  138.     165.   
## 2 body_mass_g    0.012     0.002      6.80       0    0.008    0.015
# display a table of all data points based on the Regression calculated
get_regression_points(lin_fit)
## # A tibble: 68 x 5
##       ID flipper_length_mm body_mass_g flipper_length_mm_hat residual

## 10    10               198        3700                  195.    2.57 
## # … with 58 more rows
# Show the same graph of the Chinstrap Penguins as before but with the Residual lines shown from the line of best fit to the actual points
Chinstrap_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = body_mass_g, y = flipper_length_mm)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_point(aes(y = .fitted), data = lin_fit, 
             color = "blue", shape = 2, size = 2) +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = body_mass_g ,yend = .fitted), data = lin_fit,
               color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Chinstrap Penguins",
       subtitle = "Best-Fit Line and Residuals",
       caption = "Bio 175",
       x = "body mass (in grams)",
       y = "flipper length (in mm)") +
  theme_minimal()

# calculate the overal mean of the regression data
residual_df <- get_regression_points(lin_fit)
mean(residual_df$residual)
## [1] 2.941176e-05

Loosely speaking, the best-fit line balances the positive and negative residuals.

Example: Predict the flipper length of a 4 kg Chinstrap penguin?

# prediction if body mass equals 4000
predict(lin_fit, data.frame(body_mass_g = 4000))
##        1 
## 199.0011
# prediction if body mass equals 5000 and takes into account the flipper length
lin_fit2 <- lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = penguins)
predict(lin_fit2, data.frame(body_mass_g = 5000))
##        1 
## 213.1091

Using a Categorical Variable

  • comparing the means, the 27.233 is the difference between the Gentoo mean and the Adelie mean

\[\hat{\text{flipper_length}} = b_{0} + b_{Chin} \cdot \vec{1}_{Chin} + b_{Gent} \cdot \vec{1}_{Gent}\]

indicator_df <- penguins %>%
  mutate(Adelie_ind    = ifelse(species == "Adelie",    1, 0),
         Chinstrap_ind = ifelse(species == "Chinstrap", 1, 0),
         Gentoo_ind    = ifelse(species == "Gentoo",    1, 0)) %>%
  select(species, Adelie_ind, Chinstrap_ind, Gentoo_ind)

\[\vec{1}_{Chin} = \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if penguin is of Chinstrap species} \\ 0 & \text{if penguin is not a Chinstrap} \end{cases}\]

\[\vec{1}_{Gent} = \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if penguin is of Gentoo species} \\ 0 & \text{if penguin is not a Gentoo} \end{cases}\]

Example: Predict the flipper length of a Chinstrap penguin.

predict(species_fit, data.frame(species = "Chinstrap"))
##        1 
## 195.8235
